  "slug": "danish-pastry-raspberry",
  "title": "Raspberry Danish pastries",
  "subtitle": "Laminated yeast pastry with cream cheese and raspberry jam",
  "excerpt": "Yeasted laminated pastry cut into pinwheels or rectangles, filled with a sweetened cream cheese and a spoonful of raspberry jam. The dough is made with a yeast enrichment and then folded with cold butter in the same way as croissant dough, producing layers that puff up into a distinctly flaky, crisp exterior with a soft, yeasted crumb. Finished with a simple icing sugar glaze.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Danish pastry (wienerbrød) with laminated yeast dough is documented in Scandinavian and Danish baking literature from the nineteenth century, with the butter-laminated format associated with Viennese bakers working in Copenhagen in the 1870s. Carl Sophus Lorentzen, Konditorernes Kogebog (1893, public domain), describes the laminated pastry technique. The cream cheese and jam filling variant is described in Danish and Scandinavian domestic baking guides published before 1928.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Danish pastry is croissant dough's cousin: both use the same ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "cold-butter lamination",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "term": "Laminating Danish pastry dough",
                  "termId": "cmppnlzps0000sov4zw0ftuf7"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " technique. The main difference is that Danish dough has more enrichment (eggs, milk, more sugar) and is slightly softer, which makes it more forgiving to laminate. Cold temperature throughout is the single most important factor: if the butter breaks into pieces rather than bending, it is too cold; if it smears or leaks, it is too warm.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
